<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=96688214327636></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96688214327636><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=3&mid=96688214327636>RE: Skill Point Distribution</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=3&mid=96688214327636#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Aug 21st 2:22 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.67]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>For the most part, I agree, although I wouldn't bother to put more than a point in Sense Heading.&nbsp;&nbsp;I'd throw the extra points into Mend and Bind Wound instead.<br><br>Mend gets a lot of discussion already.  All I'll say is, practice often, but be wary of critical failures.<br><br>Bind Wound heals (skill/4) hp per successful attempt, but is only usable when below 50% hp.  The good news is that monks are not limited to a skill cap of 100, as some other classes are.  The bad news is that it consumes a bandage every attempt.  A stack of bandages also weights .5, a problem for travelling light.<br><br>A partial solution is to take up Tailoring.  Two spiderling silks can be tailored into one silk thread, which only weighs .1.  When needed, combine two silk threads to make a silk bandage.  (Most monks will already be carrying a large sewing kit or two, since they're much lighter than a backpack.)<br><br><br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
	   </form></table><ul>
<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=968548375481></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f968548375481><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=3&mid=968548375481>RE: Skill Point Distribution</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=3&mid=968548375481#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=1426><span id=Scholar>Beleni</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>29 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sat, Sep 9th 9:12 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2> I usually put only one or two points into any skill, maybe five or so if it's an important one that I need right away, but usually they go up so quickly you don't need to waste the training points. Some people might put a lot into bind wound. I don't, just because that skill seems to take a lot of practice, and I figure putting ten points into it isn't going to do enough to justify it. Also, something like Kick that you won't need later on doesn't need many points of training.<br> Mend is a good one to throw those points into it, as it is a great time-reducer and might save your life more than once even at your earlier levels. When I first started practicing mend, I would save it until I needed it, like during a fight that took a turn for the worst, and like the folks mentioned here, you don't want a critical failure when you need it the most. I soon learned to practice this skill almost every time it re-freshed. Of course, I used it tactically still, so if I knew I was going up against a tough mob, I would save it for the fight, but when I wasn't in any real danger I would just keep hitting it over and over.<br> Also, for me at least, most of my skills went up very quickly after about lvl. 14. Before that, Sense heading, defense, offense, etc. would go up slowly, but when I hit 14 they all maxed out in just a few fights. So if you're low on training points, think about that and maybe you don't need to use them early on in your monking career, maybe you should save them for something like feign death ;) That's enough of my gabbing for now, have fun and maybe this will be helpful to someone.<br> Ooh, one last thing. I know that the person above mentioned the weight of bandages, but I wonder if maybe bandages aren't as heavy as they say. I usually carry around forty or so and I've never noticed them to weigh me down, but maybe I'll have to take a closer look and make sure. Just something to think about.<br><br> <br>&nbsp;<br>Beleni<br>Lowly Monk on Karana</td></tr>
